    <meta content="text/html; charset=ISO-8859-1"
      http-equiv="content-type">
    <title>NVS: Network Virtualization Substrate for Cellular Networks</title>
  </head>
  <body style=" color: rgb(0, 0, 0); background-color: rgb(255, 255,
    255);" alink="#000099" link="#000099" vlink="#990099">
    <h1 style="font-family: Shruti;"><small><span style="color: rgb(0,
          0, 153);">&nbsp;&nbsp; Wireless Resources Virtualization in
          Cellular Networks</span>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </small></h1>
    <div style="margin-left: 40px;"><font size="-1"><img style=" width:
          450px; height: 291px;" alt="" src="img/Virtualization.png"
          align="right" hspace="50" vspace="0"></font> <small
        style="font-family: Comic Sans MS;"><font style="color: rgb(0,
          0, 0);" size="-1"><small><big><big>NVS</big></big></small></font></small><font
        style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0);" size="-1"><span style="font-family:
          helvetica,arial,sans-serif;"><big style="font-family: Comic
            Sans MS;"><big></big></big> is a substrate within the
          basestation for virtualizing the wireless resources of a
          cellular network, such as a WiMAX or an LTE network.</span></font><font
        style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0);" size="-1"><span style="font-family:
          helvetica,arial,sans-serif;"> <br>
        </span></font><a style="color: rgb(51, 51, 255);"
        href="http://dl.acm.org/citation.cfm?id=1860023">Conference [ACM MobiCom 2010]</a><span
        style="color: rgb(51, 51, 255);">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <a
          href="http://ieeexplore.ieee.org/xpl/articleDetails.jsp?arnumber=6117098">Journal [TON 2012]</a></span><br>
      <br>
      <span style="font-family: Comic Sans MS;">CellSlice</span><font
        size="-1"><span style="font-family: Helvetica,Arial,sans-serif;">
          is an overlay scheduler designed for mobile core gateways to
          achieve the functionality of </span><font style="color:
          rgb(0, 0, 0);">NVS</font><span style="font-family:
          Helvetica,Arial,sans-serif;"> with minimal modifications to
          the basestations</span></font>.<br>
      <a href="PAPERS/CellSlice.pdf"><span style="color: rgb(0, 0, 238);
          text-decoration: underline;">Conference [Comsnets 2013]</span></a><br>
      <font style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0);" size="-1"><span
          style="font-family: helvetica,arial,sans-serif;"><br>
          <big>V</big>irtualizing wireless resources in cellular
          networks fosters several interesting deployment scenarios that
          are of interest to both academia and industry:</span></font><br
        style="font-family: helvetica,arial,sans-serif;">
      <ul style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0);">
        <li style="font-family: helvetica,arial,sans-serif;"><font
            size="-1">Active RAN sharing: One radical change that is
            receiving considerable attention recently is active RAN
            (Radio Access Network) sharing among Mobile Network
            Operators (MNOs). RAN sharing enables significant reduction
            in equipment in low traffic areas and results in at-least
            100% increased rollout speed with a given cost.</font><br>
        </li>
        <li style="font-family: helvetica,arial,sans-serif;"><font
            size="-1">Mobile Virtual Network Operators (MVNO): In the
            recent past, several MVNOs have emerged as strong players in
            the cellular market providing enhanced services. Such MVNOs
            often do not own spectrum and rely on sharing the wireless
            resources of a MNO in that region. Virtualization helps
            partition the wireless resources in an MNO&#8217;s network
            effectively, thereby encouraging stricter and fine-grained
            SLAs between MVNOs and MNOs.</font></li>
        <li style="font-family: helvetica,arial,sans-serif;"><font
            size="-1">Corporate Bundle Plans: Currently, network
            operators offer data plans to enterprises and corporations
            that allow sharing of bandwidth dynamically across their
            users. However, no bandwidth guarantees are provided.
            Virtualization may help realize better guarantees on
            resource allocation, and hence fosters more sophisticated
            data plans.</font></li>
        <li style="font-family: helvetica,arial,sans-serif;"><font
            size="-1"><a href="geni.html">GENI</a> and Beyond:
            Virtualization can help researchers evaluate their new ideas
            on commercial base stations and deployments.&nbsp;</font></li>
        <li style="font-family: helvetica,arial,sans-serif;"><font
            size="-1">Controlled evaluation: Virtualization enables MNOs
            to isolate partial wireless resources to deploy and test
            novel ideas without affecting the operational networks.
            Currently, MNOs often use dedicated (small scale)
            deployments to test new ideas.</font></li>
        <li><font size="-1"><span style="font-family:
              helvetica,arial,sans-serif;">Services with Leased
              Networks(SLNs): With the increased use of wireless and
              mobile networks for Internet services, we envision
              application service providers reserving bandwidth with
              MNOs and paying on the behalf of their users to enhance
              users&#8217; quality of experience. Virtualization helps in
              ensuring that such reservations are met.</span></font></li>
      </ul>
      <font style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0);" size="-1"><span
          style="font-family: helvetica,arial,sans-serif;"> </span></font><small
        style="font-family: Comic Sans MS;"><font style="color: rgb(0,
          0, 0);" size="-1"><small><big><big>NVS</big></big></small></font></small><font
        style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0);" size="-1"><span style="font-family:
          helvetica,arial,sans-serif;"> and </span></font><span
        style="font-family: Comic Sans MS;">CellSlice </span><font
        style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0);" size="-1"><span style="font-family:
          helvetica,arial,sans-serif;">enable effective wireless
          resource virtualization by meeting the following crucial
          requirements:</span></font></div>
    <ul style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:
      helvetica,arial,sans-serif; margin-left: 40px;">
      <font size="-1"> </font>
      <li><font size="-1"><span style="font-weight: bold;">Isolation</span>
          of wireless network resources across groups of flows (or
          slices) <br>
        </font></li>
      <font size="-1"> </font>
      <li><font size="-1">Efficient <span style="font-weight: bold;">utilization</span>
          of the wireless resources.</font></li>
      <font size="-1"> </font>
      <li><font size="-1"><span style="font-weight: bold;">Customization</span>
          of flow management within individual slices. <br>
        </font></li>
      <font size="-1"> </font>
    </ul>
    <div style="margin-left: 40px;"><font style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0);"
        size="-1"><span style="font-family: helvetica,arial,sans-serif;">To











          achieve the above, both </span></font><small
        style="font-family: Comic Sans MS;"><font style="color: rgb(0,
          0, 0);" size="-1"><small><big><big>NVS</big></big></small></font></small><font
        style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0);" size="-1"><span style="font-family:
          helvetica,arial,sans-serif;"> and </span></font><span
        style="font-family: Comic Sans MS;">CellSlice</span><font
        style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0);" size="-1"><span style="font-family:
          helvetica,arial,sans-serif;"> contain two novel components:</span></font><br
        style="font-family: helvetica,arial,sans-serif;">
    </div>
    <ul style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:
      helvetica,arial,sans-serif; margin-left: 40px;">
      <li><font size="-1"><span style="text-decoration: underline;">Slice











            Scheduling:</span> </font><small style="font-family: Comic
          Sans MS;"><font style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0);" size="-1"><small><big><big>NVS</big></big></small></font></small><font
          size="-1"> includes a simple and optimal slice scheduling
          algorithm that is light-weight to implement. It enables
          co-existence of both bandwidth and resource based slice
          provisioning: with bandwidth based reservation, slices can
          reserve certain amount of bandwidth in Mbps on a cellular base
          station, while resource based reservation allows slices to
          reserve a percentage of the resource slots in the OFDMA
          frames.</font></li>
      <li><font size="-1"><span style="text-decoration: underline;">Flow
            Scheduling Framework:</span> </font><small
          style="font-family: Comic Sans MS;"><font style="color: rgb(0,
            0, 0);" size="-1"><small><big><big>NVS</big></big></small></font></small><font
          size="-1"> enables individual slices to employ custom flow
          scheduling policies through a flexible framework.</font><br>
      </li>
    </ul>
    <div style="margin-left: 40px;"><font size="-1"><span style="color:
          rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: helvetica,arial,sans-serif;"> We
          instantiate the </span></font><small style="font-family:
        Comic Sans MS;"><font style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0);" size="-1"><small><big><big>NVS</big></big></small></font></small><font
        size="-1"><span style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:
          helvetica,arial,sans-serif;"> and </span></font><span
        style="font-family: Comic Sans MS;">CellSlice</span><font
        size="-1"><span style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:
          helvetica,arial,sans-serif;"> prototypes on a WiMAX testbed
          consisting of:</span></font><br style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0);
        font-family: helvetica,arial,sans-serif;">
    </div>
    <ul style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:
      helvetica,arial,sans-serif; margin-left: 40px;">
      <li><font size="-1">A Picochip&#8217;s IEEE 802.16e (WiMAX) compliant
          Base station.</font></li>
      <li><font size="-1">A Profile-C ASN-gateway installed on a Linux
          Desktop.</font></li>
      <li><font size="-1">Six Netbooks with Intel WiMAX mini PCI-X
          cards.</font></li>
      <li><font size="-1">A Video server that streams videos to the
          clients. <br>
        </font> </li>
    </ul>
    <div style="margin-left: 40px;"><font size="-1"><span style="color:
          rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: helvetica,arial,sans-serif;"></span></font><span
        style="font-family: helvetica,arial,sans-serif;"><font size="-1"><span
            style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0);">The following demos show the
            efficacy of <big style="font-family: Comic Sans MS;">NVS</big>
            on a WiMAX testbed.</span></font></span><br>
      <span style="font-family: helvetica,arial,sans-serif;"></span></div>
    <span style="font-family: helvetica,arial,sans-serif;"> </span>
    <hr style="width: 100%; height: 2px; font-family:
      helvetica,arial,sans-serif; color: rgb(0, 0, 102);">
